==English==
===Etymology===
from Latin ''dictare'', the frequentative form of ''dicere'' 'to say'
===Pronunciation===
(US) IPA: /ˈdɪkˌteɪt/
===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|dictat|e}}
#to [[order]], [[command]], [[control]]
#:''My boss thinks he can '''dictate''' how I spend my time outside work hours.''
#:''The bad weather '''dictated''' the route we travelled.''
#to [[speak]] in order for someone to [[write]] down the words
#:''She is '''dictating''' a letter to a stenographer.''
#:''The French teacher '''dictated''' a passage from Victor Hugo.''

====Derived terms====
*[[dictation]]
*[[dictator]]

====Translations====
*Finnish: [[sanella]]
*German: [[befehlen]], [[diktieren]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}
#an [[order]] or [[command]]
#:''I must obey the '''dictates''' of my conscience.''

